Put a large #frying pan{} on high heat and add a splash of @oil{a splash}. When the
oil is hot add the @British Beef Mince{250%g} to the #pan{}. Break the beef up with a
#spoon{} and cook for ~{5%minutes}. Season with a generous pinch of @salt{generous
pinch} and @pepper{generous pinch}.

While your beef is browning, get on with the rest of your prep. Cut the
@Onion{1} in half through the root. Peel and chop into ½cm cubes. Peel and grate
the @Garlic Clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{} if you have one). Remove the core from
the @Yellow Pepper{1} and cut into ½cm slices.

Once your beef is browned, add your onion and pepper to the pan and cook for
another ~{5%minutes} until your onion is soft. Stir in your garlic, @Dried Thyme{1/2%tsp}
and @Tomato Puree{1%tsp} and cook for ~{1%minute} more. Add the @Tomato Passata{1}, stir
well and reduce the heat to low.

Dissolve the @Beef Stock Pot{1/2} in boiling @Water{200%ml} and add this to the pan.
Bring your sauce to the boil and then lower the heat. Leave to simmer away for
~{20%minutes}. Your sauce will reduce and thicken in this time - this is your ragout!

Pop a large #pot{} of water on to boil. Pick the leaves from the @Basil{1} and keep
to one side. Chop your basil stalks as small as you can and add these to your ragout.

When the water comes to the boil, add a generous pinch of @salt{generous pinch} and
the @Rigatoni Pasta{160%g} and cook for ~{11%minutes} or until it is 'al dente'.

> 'Al dente' simply means the pasta is cooked through but has a tiny bit of firmness
> left in the middle.

While your pasta is cooking, prepare the salsa. Chop the @Black Olives{30} as small
as you can and chop the @Vine Tomatoes{2} into ½cm cubes, mix together in a #bowl{}.
Tear in half of your basil leaves and mix in a good glug of @oil{a good glug}. Keep to
one side.

When your pasta is cooked, drain into a #colander{} (reserve a splash of the cooking
water). Return your pasta and the cooking water to the #pot{}, off the heat and mix
well. Season with @salt{to taste} and @black pepper{to taste}. Keep to one side.

Taste your beef ragout and season with more salt and pepper if necessary. Tear in
your remaining basil leaves. Pour your beef ragout into your cooked pasta and mix
well. Serve in deep #bowls{} and top with your salsa, sprinkle over the
@Grated Hard Italian Style Cheese{40%g} and enjoy!